@rabbah currently, scan code only checks for licenses (nothing specific for python syntax/grammar on a per-line basis).  No comment syntax/validity (per language) is checked at all for any language.

Scan code also currently excludes only by whole directory (and anything below it).  Am not addressing per-file (as this is a new requirement to me as of this discussion), would be an enhancement going forward.  Hopefully, having a license header in a file or two (where it does not much matter if it has one or not) should not be a showstopper for general license checking for Python.  If a file has one line of code that can be treated as "IP", again that would mean we are discussing only "badcomment", and it does not hurt having one there.  If we ever enable per-file exclusion, then we can delete it, but really no one will likely care if the test works going forward.

Planned on enabling .js license header checking after Python was done BTW (and add to every .js file) then go back to changing/checking for in existing supported languages (by file extension).  If you want to open an issue to do additional checks on Scancode (per-line comment as one); I would be happy to look at later (truthful, as I am having fun with scancode)...
